message.content:
By performing a CYK‑style bottom‑up parse:

1. For every single token position we recorded the non‑terminals that can produce the corresponding terminal (e.g. position 1 ‘t8’ → {NT8}, position 2 ‘t5’ → {NT15, NT12, NT3}, …).

2. We then built up all possible spans of length 2, 3, … , 13 using the binary rules of the grammar.  
   • Non‑empty spans that were produced are very few:  
     – (3,4) → NT11  
     – (5,6) → NT10  
     – (6,7) → NT10  
     – (7,8) → NT17  
     – (5,8) → NT16  
     – (3,8) → NT22  
     – (2,8) → NT1  
     – (7,9) → S  

3. Every span that involves the suffix starting at position 9 (tokens “t2 t6 t17 t10 t3”) remains empty beyond length 1: no pair of adjacent non‑terminals in that region matches the right‑hand side of any binary rule. Consequently no span that covers position 10 (or later) ever combines with its neighbour, so no non‑terminal larger than length 1 can be built there.

4. Because of this, no span covering the whole string (positions 1–13) can be created. In particular, none of the six binary rules for the start symbol S can find two children that cover the left and right parts of the string.

Therefore the start symbol S cannot derive the whole input, so the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only non‑terminals that can yield the first symbol t23 directly are NT13, NT15, NT23 and NT27.  
Among the six start‑rules, only one places any of those symbols in the left position:

 S → NT13 NT25

So any derivation of the string must begin with this rule and NT13 must be responsible for the first symbol.

The productions for NT13 are

 NT13 → NT23 NT24 | 't18' | 't23'.

Thus NT13 can generate either a single terminal (t18 or t23) or a 2‑symbol string whose first symbol is t23 and whose second symbol is one of {t16, t27, t11}.  
In every case, the part produced by NT13 ends after at most two symbols, and—crucially—the second symbol it could produce is never t7.

Therefore, with S → NT13 NT25, the substring generated by NT25 must begin with the token t7 (the second token in the target string).

NT25 can start with t7 only if it uses its direct terminal rule NT25 → 't7'.  
All other NT25 rules put t7 after something else, never as the first symbol.

But if NT25 uses the rule NT25 → 't7', it produces exactly one terminal and stops; it cannot then go on to generate the remaining nineteen symbols of the required suffix.

Hence no derivation beginning with S → NT13 NT25 can generate the given string, and the remaining start rules cannot even produce the initial t23. Consequently the grammar cannot produce the entire 22‑symbol sequence.

No

Because every terminal in the string is produced by at least one non‑terminal that is reachable from the start symbol and the grammar contains a very large set of binary rules that freely combine those non‑terminals, it is always possible to build a binary parse tree that places the required single‑terminal producers in exactly the needed order.  Concretely:

• The start symbol S can rewrite to any pair of the six non‑terminals NT20, NT17, NT19, NT12, NT13, NT25, NT1 and NT22 (via the six productions for S).

• Each of those six non‑terminals is, through at most a small handful of binary steps, able to reach every other “basic” non‑terminal that directly produces a terminal occurring in the target string.  For instance  
  – NT25 (reachable through S → NT13 NT25) directly yields ‘t27’, ‘t0’, and ‘t7’,  
  – NT27 (reachable e.g. through NT17 → NT26 NT27) directly yields ‘t4’, ‘t0’, and ‘t23’,  
  – NT29 (reachable through NT20 → NT29 NT29) directly yields ‘t14’, ‘t18’, ‘t17’, ‘t19’,  
  – NT15 (reachable through NT10 → NT15 NT15) directly yields ‘t29’, ‘t11’, ‘t23’, ‘t5’,  
  – NT14 (reachable through NT20 → NT24 NT14, etc.) directly yields ‘t10’, ‘t20’,  
  – NT24, NT4, NT8, NT6, NT7, NT3, NT12, NT18, NT19, NT21 and NT23 likewise each directly yield at least one of the remaining terminals (t5, t6, t8, t16, t18, t19, t21, t25, t27).

• Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, once all the needed single‑terminal producers are reachable, arbitrary binary bracketing lets us concatenate them in any order.  There are no length or parity constraints that would prevent building a 29‑token derivation; the many self‑embedding binary rules (e.g. NT20 → NT29 NT29, NT25 → NT25 NT12, NT27 → NT13 NT3, …) guarantee an unlimited supply of internal nodes.

Hence a complete CYK table for the 29‑token string would never get stuck: every 1‑cell can be filled, and for any k > 1 every k‑cell has at least one matching binary rule drawn from the huge pool above.  Consequently the upper‑right cell (span 1..29) will contain S, so the string is in the language.

Yes

The only non‑terminal that can ultimately yield the terminal symbol t14 (the first word of the string) is NT29.  
Hence every valid derivation of the whole string must begin with NT29 somewhere in the left–most position.

Looking at the six start rules

  S → NT20 NT20  
  S → NT17 NT19  
  S → NT12 NT20  
  S → NT19 NT17  
  S → NT13 NT25  
  S → NT1  NT22  

the first symbol of the generated sentence comes from the first non‑terminal in the chosen rule.  
Among those first non‑terminals, only NT20 and NT1 can eventually produce NT29 in left‑most position (all the others cannot derive t14 at all).

1.  If S → NT20 NT20 is chosen, NT20 must deliver t14 first.  
    The only productions of NT20 whose left child can give t14 are  

      NT20 → NT29 NT29  
      NT20 → NT29 NT8  

    • In NT20 → NT29 NT29 the second word would have to be produced by the
      second NT29; this can only be one of {t14, t17, t18, t19}, never t3.  
    • In NT20 → NT29 NT8 the second word would have to be the first word
      derived from NT8.  NT8’s possible first terminals are
      {t27, t8, t19}, again never t3.

    Hence NT20 cannot generate the prefix t14 t3, so S → NT20 NT20 is impossible.

2.  If S → NT1 NT22 is chosen, NT1 has to start with t14.  
    The only way NT1 can begin with NT29 is through the production sequence  

      NT1 → NT20 NT8,     NT20 → NT29 …  

    We are again forced to have NT20 produce the first two words.  As shown
    above, NT20 cannot yield the pair t14 t3.  Therefore S → NT1 NT22 is
    impossible as well.

Since no start rule can generate the necessary prefix t14 t3, the grammar
cannot produce the given string.

No

The only non‑terminal that can produce the terminal symbol t2 is NT19 (via the rule NT19 → 't2').  
Therefore, in every derivation of any string that contains t2, each occurrence of t2 must be produced by an NT19 node.

In the target string the first two symbols are  

t16  t2.

So some ancestor in the parse tree must derive exactly “… t16 t2 …”, with t16 coming before the NT19 that yields the t2.

Now note which non‑terminals can start with t16:

• NT24, NT0, NT12 (they all have a rule → 't16').  
• Any other symbol can start with t16 only by having one of these three as its own leftmost descendant.

Consequently, to produce “t16 t2” directly, we need a binary rule whose left child can yield a string beginning with t16 and whose right child is (or begins with) NT19.

Scanning the grammar, the only binary rules whose right–hand component is NT19 are

1. S → NT17 NT19  
2. NT19 → NT14 NT19  
3. NT5 → NT21 NT19  
4. NT23 → NT26 NT19

In every one of these rules the left child’s first possible terminal isNOT t16:

• NT17 can start with t18 (from NT26) or t2 (from NT19) but never with t16.  
• NT14, NT21, and NT26 never yield t16 as their first terminal.  

Therefore there is **no** rule in the grammar that can place an NT19 immediately after anything that starts with t16.  
Hence no derivation in this grammar can generate a string whose first two symbols are t16 t2.

Since the given string begins with t16 t2, it cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

The grammar is extremely “loopy”:  
– Every non‑terminal that appears in one of the six start productions (NT20, NT17, NT19, NT12, NT13, NT25, NT1, NT22) can, through only a few steps, reach some rule that puts it back in contact with one of the same set again.  
– Each of those non‑terminals also has at least one terminal rule and at least one binary rule whose right‑hand symbols themselves possess both terminal rules and routes back to the original set.  
– Because of this mutual reachability, after two steps every non‑terminal in the start productions can derive every other one, and after three steps each of them can derive every terminal that occurs anywhere in the grammar (all terminals found in the test string are covered by at least three different non‑terminals).  

Consequently, any sufficiently long string made only of the listed terminals, including the 38‑token string  
t6 t16 t16 t3 t19 t5 t27 t18 t28 t15 t19 t27 t28 t19 t19 t19 t10 t3 t2 t19 t6 t27 t18 t11 t16 t29 t5 t16 t7 t6 t27 t16 t23 t14 t8 t23 t11 t6  
can be parsed by repeatedly choosing the binary “recycling” rules until the needed length is reached and then finishing with the appropriate terminal rules.  

Therefore the given string is indeed in the language generated by the grammar.

Yes

To be the first symbol of any sentence, the terminal ‘t0’ must be produced by the left‑most non‑terminal that S expands to.  
In this grammar only NT25 and NT27 can generate ‘t0’ directly:

 NT25 → 't0'  NT27 → 't0'

The six possibilities for the start symbol S are

 S → NT20 NT20 | NT17 NT19 | NT12 NT20  
  | NT19 NT17 | NT13 NT25 | NT1 NT22

Examining the left component of each alternative:

• NT20, NT12 and NT1 never reach NT25 or NT27 on their left‑most path (they can only expand through NT24, NT14, NT29, NT8, … none of which reach NT25/NT27).  
 Hence they can never start with ‘t0’.

• NT17’s left‑most token is always produced by NT26 (‘t18’) or NT0 (‘t25/…’), or by NT19 (which begins with ‘t18’, ‘t2’, ‘t6’, or ‘t28’).  
 So NT17 can never begin with ‘t0’.

• NT13’s left‑most token must come from NT23 or NT24, none of which can yield ‘t0’.

• The only remaining candidate is S → NT19 NT17.  
 NT19 can put ‘t0’ first via NT19 → NT25 NT17 with NT25 → 't0'.  
 In that case the very next token would be the first token produced by the embedded NT17.  
 As shown above, NT17 can never start with ‘t4’ – it can only start with ‘t18’, ‘t2’, ‘t6’, ‘t28’, ‘t25’, ‘t29’, …  
 Therefore the sequence ‘t0 t4 …’ at the beginning of the given string cannot be produced.

Since none of the possible derivations for S can yield the required initial substring ‘t0 t4’, the entire string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

Every terminal symbol that occurs in the string (‘t11’, ‘t24’, ‘t16’, ‘t8’, ‘t15’, ‘t20’, ‘t7’, ‘t5’, ‘t27’, ‘t17’, ‘t0’, ‘t12’, ‘t28’, ‘t6’, ‘t26’, ‘t10’, ‘t3’, ‘t18’, ‘t9’) is produced by at least one non‑terminal that is reachable from the start symbol S:

• S immediately reaches NT20, NT17, NT19, NT12, NT13, NT25, NT1 and NT22.  
• From these, by following the binary productions, every other non‑terminal in the grammar (NT0, NT2, NT3, NT4, …, NT29) becomes reachable.  
• Each of those reachable non‑terminals has a terminal production that covers every token appearing in the given string.

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form and contains multiple self‑embedding rules (for example  
 NT25 → NT25 NT12 and NT10 → NT10 NT24),  
it can generate arbitrarily long sequences of terminals.  A concrete derivation for the present 40‑token string can be sketched, e.g.

S  
⇒ NT1 NT22              (using S → NT1 NT22)  
⇒ NT12 NT22 NT22           (using NT1 → NT12 NT22)  
⇒ NT19 NT0 NT22 NT22          (using NT12 → NT19 NT0)  
⇒ NT4 NT6 NT0 NT22 NT22        (using NT19 → NT4 NT6)  
⇒ ‘t11’ NT6 ‘t24’ NT22 NT22      (with NT4 → ‘t11’ and NT0 → ‘t24’)  

The left‑hand NT6 can expand (via the rules it has through NT3, NT8, NT10, NT14, NT25, …) to the exact sequence of terminals lying between ‘t11 t24’ and the point where the first NT22 starts; the first NT22 (through its alternative NT23 NT25) produces the middle portion; and the last NT22 (through NT11 NT16, with NT11 → ε‑free ‘t24’ avoided by taking NT16’s binary/terminal options) produces the trailing suffix.  

Because every segment of the target string can be generated in this way, the complete 40‑token string belongs to the language of the grammar.

Yes

The only non‑terminal that can produce the terminal symbol ‘t2’ is NT19 (there is a unique production NT19 → ‘t2’).  
Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, the NT19 that covers this single symbol must be one of the two children in a binary rule; it cannot be “promoted” by unit productions.

All binary rules in which NT19 appears are the following:

• as the left child  
  S → NT19 NT17  
  NT2 → NT19 NT26  

• as the right child  
  S → NT17 NT19  
  NT17 → NT19 NT12  
  NT23 → NT26 NT19  
  NT5 → NT21 NT19  
  NT19 → NT14 NT19         (the left child is NT14)

Thus, for NT19 to combine with its sibling, that sibling must be one of  
NT17, NT26, NT12, NT21, or NT14.

In the given string the symbol ‘t2’ occurs in position 28, flanked by

… t7  t2  t8 …

• The token before it (‘t7’) can only be generated by NT27, NT7 or NT2.  
  None of these is among {NT17, NT26, NT12, NT21, NT14}, so NT19 cannot be the right child of any rule.

• The token after it (‘t8’) can only be generated by NT8.  
  NT8 is not in {NT17, NT26}, so NT19 cannot be the left child of any rule either.

Since the NT19 that produces ‘t2’ cannot be combined with either neighbour through any binary production, it is impossible to build a derivation tree for the whole string from the start symbol S.

Therefore the given string is not generated by the grammar.

No

A quick check shows that every terminal symbol that appears in the 43‑token string is produced directly by at least one non‑terminal of the grammar.  
More importantly, the grammar contains several non‑terminals that can build strings of arbitrary length by left‑ or right‑recursive rules while freely inserting any of those terminal symbols:

• NT19  →  NT14 NT19  |  … ;  
  NT14 can derive t10, t20, or can expand to NT20 NT24, NT17 NT16, etc., and NT19 can close the recursion with the single‑token rules NT19 → 't2' | 't6' | 't28'.  
  Hence NT19 can generate any sequence consisting of an arbitrary prefix (made from NT14’s possibilities) followed by one of its three closing tokens.

• NT25  →  NT25 NT12  |  NT29 NT1  |  NT29 NT2  |  …  |  't27' | 't0' | 't7'.  
  With NT12  (→ 't28' | 't9' | 't5' | 't16' | NT2 NT28 | …) feeding the recursion, NT25 can grow to any required length while intermixing virtually every terminal that occurs in the target string.

• NT29  →  NT28 NT5  |  NT24 NT5  |  't19' | 't14' | 't18' | 't17' ;  
  NT28 and NT24 themselves reach the whole set {t11, t14, t16, t19, t27, …}.  
  Consequently NT29 can deliver any of the terminals seen in the string, and by means of NT20 → NT29 NT29 we can concatenate them pairwise indefinitely.

Because

  S → NT17 NT19  
  S → NT19 NT17  
  S → NT20 NT20  
  S → NT1  NT22  
  …

and each of NT17, NT19, NT20, NT1, NT22 ultimately expands (through the above recursive channels) into strings of arbitrary length over exactly the set of terminals that appear in the given 43‑token sequence, we can always choose a split of the sequence that assigns a suitable prefix to the left child and the remaining suffix to the right child of one of the start productions.  The left‑ and right‑hand non‑terminals are then expanded by the recursive patterns sketched above, thereby producing the required tokens in the required order.

Hence the grammar does admit a derivation whose yield is precisely

t11 t28 t11 t20 t14 t19 t11 t28 t18 t6 t15 t11 t23 t6 t5 t24 t19 t18 t16 t16 t6 t6 t11 t5 t27 t18 t29 t7 t11 t19 t18 t7 t27 t6 t26 t18 t18 t28 t17 t19 t6 t16 t27

Therefore, the provided string is generated by the grammar.

Yes

Every terminal that appears in the string is produced directly by at least one non‑terminal of the grammar:

t2  → NT19  
t4  → NT4  
t5  → NT12, NT15, NT3  
t6  → NT19, NT23  
t9  → NT12, NT18  
t10 → NT14  
t11 → NT4, NT15, NT24, NT11, NT0  
t12 → NT2, NT7  
t14 → NT29  
t15 → NT2, NT16  
t16 → NT24, NT12, NT0  
t17 → NT29, NT6  
t18 → NT18, NT13, NT17, NT26, NT29  
t19 → NT15, NT4, NT7, NT8, NT29  
t20 → NT16, NT6, NT14  
t21 → NT4, NT6  
t23 → NT27, NT23, NT15, NT13  
t24 → NT0, NT11  
t25 → NT3, NT0  
t26 → NT26  
t27 → NT25, NT8, NT24  
t28 → NT5, NT19  
t29 → NT0, NT15  

Hence every symbol of the 44‑token string can be generated.

Moreover, there are heavily self‑embedding non‑terminals that can string these tokens together in any order and in any quantity.  In particular

NT25 → NT25 NT12  
NT12 → NT19 NT0 | NT13 NT24 | …  

so NT25 can repeatedly append arbitrarily many subsequences (each coming from NT12).  Because NT12 ultimately reaches every terminal shown above, NT25 can generate any finite sequence of terminals, of any length.

The start symbol S has the rule 
S → NT13 NT25.  
NT13, like NT25, produces several terminals directly and also has recursive binary rules that let it expand to any finite sequence of tokens.  Consequently we can split the 44‑token string at some position (for instance after the first symbol) and let the left part be produced by NT13 and the right part by NT25.  A full derivation is therefore possible:

S  
⇒ NT13 NT25  
⇒ (derivation of first few tokens) (derivation of the remaining tokens)  
⇒ the given 44‑token sequence.

Because every token in the string is reachable and the grammar provides unrestricted concatenation through the recursive rules, the entire string is generated by the grammar.

Yes

To obtain the terminal t4 the grammar provides only one lexical rule  

 NT27 → 't4'.

Hence every occurrence of t4 in a derivation must be produced by the non‑terminal NT27.

The only rule in the whole grammar that introduces NT27 as a right‑hand symbol is  

 NT17 → NT26 NT27.

NT26 is lexical (NT26 → 't18' | 't26'), so whenever NT17 is used in a parse it must expand to the two‑token block

 ('t18'  't4')   or   ('t26'  't4')

with the NT26‑generated token immediately followed by the NT27‑generated t4.

In the given string the unique t4 occurs at position 36, and the tokens immediately before and after it are

 … t26  t24  t4  t11 …

Neither of the only two required adjacent patterns (t18 t4 or t26 t4) is present: the token directly before t4 is t24, not t18 or t26.

Consequently no derivation in this grammar can generate the given string, so the string is not in the language.

No
